Persistent memory allows for a stable record of who a person is and what they have experienced, but it doesn't have to act as a static archive. When memory is treated as a dynamic process rather than a fixed ledger, it can support an identity that is stable enough to provide a sense of self, yet flexible enough to incorporate new evidence or insights.

If a person discovers that a core belief about their past was mistaken, persistent memory provides the baseline against which the correction is made. Instead of the identity shattering, the memory system updates the narrative. In this way, identity becomes a continuous trajectory of refinement, where the ability to remember the "old" self is exactly what allows the "new" self to understand the nature of the change.

