Retaining information is essentially a storage problem—keeping a record intact so it can be retrieved. However, allowing remembered relationships to remain correctable is a dynamic process. It means the system doesn't just store a static snapshot, but maintains the "connective tissue" between ideas in a way that allows new evidence to reshape how those ideas relate to one another without destroying the underlying data.

One is like a read-only archive; the other is like a living map that updates its topography as the landscape changes.

